class Image(object):
    def __init__(self, path):
        self.path = path
        self.bgr_img = None
        self.gray_image = None
        self.rgb_image = None
    def read_image(self, return_img=False):
        #Load an color image 
        self.bgr_img = cv2.imread(self.path)
        if return_img:
            return self.bgr_img
    def rgb(self, return_img=False):
        self.rgb_image = cv2.cvtColor(self.bgr_img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)    
        if return_img:
            return self.rgb_image           
    def gray(self, return_img=False):
        self.gray_image = cv2.cvtColor(self.bgr_img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
        if return_img:
            return self.gray_image
    def show(self, img, title='image'):
            if len(img.shape) != 3:
                plt.imshow(img, cmap='gray')
            else:
                 plt.imshow(img) 
            plt.title(title)
            plt.show()
    def Show_all(self, image_list, title_list):
        plt.figure(figsize=[20,10])
        assert len(image_list) == len(title_list),"Houston we've got a problem"
        N = len(image_list)
        for index, (img, title) in enumerate(zip(image_list, title_list)):
            plt.subplot(1, N, index+1)
            if len(img.shape) != 3:
                plt.imshow(img, cmap='gray')
            else:
                plt.imshow(img)
            plt.title(title)
        plt.show()

def convolve2d(image, kernel):
    image_r = image.shape[0]
    image_c = image.shape[1]
    kernel_r = kernel.shape[0]
    kernel_c = kernel.shape[1]
    image_equalized = image/np.max(np.abs(image))
    
    a=image_r + kernel_r - 1
    b=image_c + kernel_c - 1
    image_with_pad = np.zeros([a,b])  
    
    c=kernel_r//2
    d= kernel_c//2
    image_with_pad[c:-(c),d:-(d)] = image_equalized
    
    image_translation = np.zeros([image_r, image_c])
    for r in range(image_r):
        for c in range(image_c):
            mysum = 0
            for m in range(kernel_r):
                for n in range(kernel_c):
                    mysum += kernel[m][n] * image_with_pad[m + r][n + c]
            image_translation[r][c] = mysum
    return image_translation

Canny edge detection

In [13]:
gray = image.gray(return_img=True)
edges1=cv2.Canny(gray,50,150)
edges2=cv2.Canny(gray,100,200)
edges3=cv2.Canny(gray,150,250)

image.Show_all([edges1, edges2, edges3], ['Canny 50/150', 
                                          'Canny 100/200',
                                          'Canny 150/250'])

Explanation: Canny uses two threshold to find the continuous edges. The edge pixels above the upper limit are considered in an edge map and edge pixels below the threshold are discarded. pixels inbetween upper and lower threshold are considered only if they are connected to pixels in upper threshold, otherwise they are being zeroed out.

if we choose the thresholds correctly in, we get a clean edge map.
